-- Air France, Lufthansa, L'Oreal SA, Zodiac Aerospace: Europe Equity Preview
-- B y   T a r a   L a c h a p e l l e
-- 2010-09-21T04:00:01Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-20/air-france-lufthansa-l-oreal-sa-zodiac-aerospace-europe-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  rose 1.3 percent to 266.22. The
 Stoxx 50 Index  gained 1.3 percent to 2,571.04. The  Euro Stoxx 50
Index , a benchmark for nations using the euro, added 1.6 percent
to 2,802.67.  Air France-KLM Group  (AF FP): Europe’s largest airline will
cancel some short- and medium-haul flights on Sept. 23 at the
request of the French civil aviation authority because of a
general strike to protest pension reforms that may include
action by some air-traffic controllers. The shares rose 1.1
percent to 11.37 euros.  Biocompatibles International Plc  (BII LN): The drugmaker
said it has received a “preliminary approach” that may lead to
an offer being made for the company. The shares advanced 6.3
percent to 327.5 pence.  Draka Holding NV  (DRAK NA): Europe’s third-largest cable
maker said it plans to appoint a chief financial officer and
Chief Operating Officer Okke Koo will step down as of January.
Draka gained 2.1 percent to 11.52 euros.  Deutsche Bank AG  (DBK GY): Germany’s largest lender said it
will raise about 10.2 billion euros ($13.3 billion) in the
company’s biggest-ever share sale to take over Deutsche Postbank
AG and prepare for tougher capital rules. The shares added 1.5
percent to 46.88 euros.  Deutsche Lufthansa AG  (LHA GY): Europe’s second-biggest
airline plans to propose  Christoph Franz  as successor to Chief
Executive Officer  Wolfgang Mayrhuber  at a supervisory board
meeting this week, according to a person familiar with the
matter. The stock rallied 1.1 percent to 13.35 euros.  Dexia SA  (DEXB BB): Dexia Bank Belgium was acquitted by the
Ghent appeals court in the Lernout & Hauspie Speech Products NV
case. Lernout & Hauspie co-founders  Jo Lernout  and  Pol Hauspie 
were found guilty of accounting fraud by the court.  Dexia shares will resume trading after being suspended on
Sept. 18. The shares of Belgium’s biggest bank by assets dropped
3.1 percent to 3.23 euros on Sept. 17.  Floridienne SA  (FLOB BB): The holding company’s Floridienne
Chimie SA unit said it will build new production plants for
cadmium salts and zinc salts. The units should be ready for
production in February. Floridienne rose 4.2 percent to 125
euros.  Legrand SA  (LR FP): Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. and
 Wendel  (MF FP) said they’re selling 23.7 million Legrand shares,
or about 9 percent of the maker of electrical equipment, to
institutional investors and will retain about 36.5 percent of
the company and 52 percent of voting rights after the
transaction. Legrand shares rose 1.4 percent to 25.10 euros.
Wendel shares added 2.4 percent to 46.35 euros.  London Stock Exchange Group Plc  (LSE LN): Europe’s oldest
independent bourse is the “frontrunner” to be the partner of
Mongolia’s stock exchange, which the country plans to open by
year-end, Prime Minister Sukhbaatar Batbold said in a briefing
in New York. The shares rose 2.5 percent to 693 pence.  L’Oreal SA  (OR FP): The world’s largest cosmetics maker
ended all contracts with Francois-Marie Banier, a photographer
and author who has been accused of allegedly manipulating the
company’s largest shareholder into giving him gifts worth 1
billion euros. The shares gained 2.7 percent to 84.89 euros.  Minerva Plc  (MNR LN): The second-biggest developer of
office space in central London is scheduled to report full-year
earnings. The stock climbed 5.4 percent to 98 pence.  Xstrata Plc  (XTA LN): The largest exporter of coal used for
power plans to increase the amount of loans it’s seeking to
refinance debt by a third to $4 billion, two people familiar
with the matter said. The shares advanced 2.1 percent to 1,191
pence.  Zodiac Aerospace  (ZC FP): The maker of aircraft equipment
and cabin interiors said sales in the year through August fell
to 2.15 billion euros from 2.21 billion euros, and forecast an
operating margin of about 11 percent of sales. The shares fell
1.3 percent to 46.88 euros.  To contact the reporters on this story:
 Tara Lachapelle  in New York at 
 tlachapelle@bloomberg.net  